<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">VEP 0016</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Wri</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">en Submission by Paul Langton VEP 0016</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.75pt">Executive Summary:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This contribution examines some of the issues regarding prisoners’ right to vote from a layman’s perspective. It supports the argument that the UK should comply with the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Hirst</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> ruling of the European Court of Human Rights (ECtHR) and rejects all three options contained in the draft bill. A proposal is offered that prisoners detained in open prisons should be offered a conditional right to vote, as part of a process of rehabilitation, drawing on contributions advanced in the commons debate on 10th February 2011 and the judgement of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola v Italy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (no. 3).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.75pt">About the submitter: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I am a layman with an interest in democratic and constitutional reform and have been following the developments in the case of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Hirst v. The United Kingdom (no.2)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> since 2010.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><img src="data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAnYAAAACCAYAAADVeJEHAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAAA5SURBVFhH7daxDQAABEXBv//SFCxBTiL6yyskM2UZaEADGtCABjSggbMN7EvnECBAgAABAgQIvBBo83RwrIgD9lgAAAAASUVORK5CYII=" width="629" height="2" alt="" style="margin-left:1.15pt; margin-top:6.45pt; position:absolute; z-index:0" /></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The matter of granting prisoners the right to vote following the judgement of the European Court of Human Rights (ECtHR) is a contentious one. Arguments have been advanced that:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“..If you break the law, you cannot make the law”</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“…we discovered absolutely no demand from prisoners for that so-called right”</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“…By extending its [ECtHR] remit into areas way beyond any original conception of fundamental human rights, the Court in Strasbourg is undermining its own legitimacy and its potential effectiveness”</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Democracy and democratic rights are evolving concepts. Our current system of electoral enfranchisement is less than 100 years old </span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and should be regarded as a “work in progress”. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Legal challenges ensure that laws remain relevant, proportionate and fit for purpose for the 21</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Century. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The judgement of the European Court of Human Rights presents Parliament with a challenge but also an opportunity to engage with the issue of democratic reform in the consideration of the right to vote for prisoners.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I do not believe that all prisoners should be enfranchised as a consequence of the ECtHR ruling. Aside from the opposition from members of the Commons, the public and the media, such a proposal would be incomprehensible.  Just as the criticism of the “blanket ban” is based on the observation that it: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“...applies automatically to such prisoners, irrespective of the length of their sentence </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">irrespective of the nature or gravity of their offence and their individual circumstances”</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Then an enfranchisement of all prisoners could be seen as an inversion of the position with its justification holding the same shortcomings.  Indeed it was never the Court’s intention to enfranchise all prisoners:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“…the rights bestowed by Article 3 of Protocol No. 1 are not absolute. There is room for implied limitations and Contracting States must be allowed a margin of appreciation in this sphere”</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">However, from my assessment of the draft bill I consider the options that have been offered to be inadequate in this debate. I discuss my reasons in detail below. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The draft bill suffers from the same shortcomings of the second consultation on prisoners’ voting rights in 2009 by the Labour Government, in that it focuses primarily on the length of sentence in relation to disenfranchisement. Such restricted options suggest a reluctance of the Government to engage seriously with the Courts’ judgement and with the wider topic of prison reform.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The limits of 6 months and 4 years have been arbitrarily chosen. The dissenting judge observed in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola v Italy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that the Italian system of disenfranchisement: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“…is a blunt instrument stripping of their Convention right to vote a significant number of persons and doing so in an indiscriminate manner and to a large extent regardless of the nature of their crimes, the length of their sentences and their individual circumstances”</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Although this was not enough to sway the rest of the Court who did not find a breach of Article 3, protocol 1 in that case.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Furthermore the linking of a specified sentence length to disenfranchisement was the least popular option in the first stage of the Labour Government consultation with only 4 respondents from 88 expressing a preference for such a system</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I also do not accept that a restatement of the “blanket ban” is a viable option. The current arrangements have already been described by the 2011 House of Commons Political and Constitutional Reform Committee as: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“…illegal under international law founded on the UK’s treaty obligations”.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Attorney General Dominic Grieve noted in the debate on the 10th February 2011 that:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“...the judgments of the Court constitute an international obligation, so far as we subscribe to the convention and to membership of the Council of Europe”.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">And the Joint Committee on Human Rights (2006-7) stated that:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“…It is also a matter for regret that the Government should seek views on retaining the current blanket ban, thereby raising expectations that this could be achieved, when in fact, this is the one option explicitly ruled out by the European Court”.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The judgement as given in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Hirst</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> determined that a “blanket ban” was:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“..a general, automatic and indiscriminate restriction on a vitally important Convention right must be seen as falling outside </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">any</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> acceptable margin of appreciation, however wide that margin might be, and as being incompatible with Article 3 of Protocol No. 1”</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">To restate the existing ban – or to pass legislation that grants the vote but effectively maintains a “blanket restriction” - would be to ignore the judgement of the Court. This could have serious international consequences:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“…it would be a great pity if a long-established State—the United Kingdom, which was there at the founding and there at the drafting—were to set an example to other States in the Council of Europe that they do not have to abide by the law”</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Such a move would signify an uncomfortable departure from the UK’s observance of the “rule of law” which in the opinion of Lord Mackay should be respected at both a domestic and European level:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“…if we believe in the rule of law, we are just as much bound to observe the decisions of the European Court on matters within their competence as we are to obey the decisions of our own courts in matters within their competence”.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Some MP’s have suggested that as the European Court of Human Rights lacks any means to enforce the judgement then the option is open for the matter to rest as an un-implemented decision</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">However it has been noted by Attorney General Dominic Grieve in the commons debate of 10</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> February 2011 that:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“…It is therefore a bit of a red herring to suggest that just because something cannot be enforced, that is a justification for ignoring it. It might be a justification for enacting other legislation or taking other steps, but it would be a fairly momentous change in UK </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">practice if we ignored something to which we had indicated by international treaty we subscribe”</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">At present the UK’s current position on the ban is opening the Government to litigation with two prisoners, serving life sentences for murder, challenging the Government in the Supreme Court on the right to vote</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Concerning the decision of the UK of granting prisoners the right to vote I am sympathetic to this view </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">if</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> it was in the context of serving a rehabilitative purpose by preparing prisoners for release. I am also sympathetic to the view that if some prisoners are granted privileges, that are denied others, due to their conduct in prison and “good behaviour” then they ought to be considered for the right to vote. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The state categorizes prisoners according to their assessed level of security risk, determines whether they should be held in a closed or open facility and what privileges they may be allowed</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Parole hearings determine when an offender can leave prison</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and discretion is applied when granting temporary release to aid resettlement</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  A prisoner’s behaviour is continually assessed and treatment and privileges bestowed at the discretion of the institution in accordance to set guidelines. Consequently prisoners are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">not </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">treated uniformly with individual treatment varying during the serving of a sentence.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Sentencing in non-custodial cases can vary with the imposition of conditions that require an offender to participate in a rehabilitation programme. For example: in drink / driving offences it  is possible for a court, with an offenders agreement, to reduce the period by which the offender is disqualified from driving by up to one quarter on successful completion of a course under the drink / drive rehabilitation scheme</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">With this in mind it is my view that those prisoners who are closest to society, and who have been assessed and afforded the highest level of trust by the state, should be granted the consideration of having the right to vote restored to them. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">An open prison where the focus is on education, training and working in the community offers a population that would be the most likely to benefit from the right to vote . As Governor Graham Batchford of North Sea Camp remarked on open prisons in 2011:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“…It's about reintegrating them back into the community, breaking them back into society gently."</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The granting of the right to vote would be a significant and symbolic step towards achieving this goal.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Gordon Henderson MP, ironically a member opposed to votes for prisoners, assessed the benefits of granting the vote to those prisoners held in an open prison. I fully concur with his analysis and quote in part from the debate held in the Commons on 10</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> February 2011:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“…Such an approach would have a number of advantages. First, it would obey the European Court of Human Rights' ruling by giving the vote to the majority of prisoners at some stage in their sentence. Secondly, it would allow the vote to those convicted of relatively minor offences and sent to open prison. Thirdly, it would address the arguments of those who claim that giving the vote to prisoners would encourage them to become useful members of society-which it does. Fourthly, it would deny the vote to those convicted of the most heinous crimes until they had served most of their sentence and were about to be released back into the community, when they would get the vote anyway”</span><a name="_ftnref23"></a><a href="#_ftn23">[23]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">To some extent this was advanced by Naomi Long MP earlier in the same debate:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“…A preferable option, bearing in mind the rehabilitation argument, may be to limit the right of voting to prisoners serving sentences of one year or less, and to reintroduce the right to vote in the final year of a longer sentence as part of a wider programme of reintegration and rehabilitation”</span><a name="_ftnref24"></a><a href="#_ftn24">[24]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Notably the question of rehabilitation was an influential factor in the Courts decision in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola v Italy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> as:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“… the Court cannot underestimate the fact that under Italian law it is possible for a convicted person who has been permanently deprived of the right to vote to recover that right”</span><a name="_ftnref25"></a><a href="#_ftn25">[25]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">And that convicted persons under an early release scheme: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“…can apply for rehabilitation and, where applicable, recover the right to vote at an earlier date. In the Court’s opinion this possibility shows that the Italian system is not excessively rigid”.</span><a name="_ftnref26"></a><a href="#_ftn26">[26]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This involves participating in a course of “re-education”:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“…In order to facilitate reintegration into society, convicted prisoners who take part in the re-education scheme may have their sentence reduced by forty-five days for every six months served ...”</span><a name="_ftnref27"></a><a href="#_ftn27">[27]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Granting prisoners the right to vote has to be neither uniform, nor unconditional.  It could be restricted to those serving their in sentence in an open prison. In addition enfranchisement could be conditional on the offender completing a relevant course – such as citizenship education, which actively promotes knowledge and understanding of the law, democracy and public life</span><a name="_ftnref28"></a><a href="#_ftn28">[28]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A logical step, if the Government and Parliament intend to comply with the ruling of the European Court, is to adopt a rehabilitative approach which is offered by the margin of appreciation. By incorporating the enfranchisement of prisoners within this wider goal of rehabilitation, and resisting the temptation to resort to the “blunt instrument” of sentence length, the Government can recognise a prisoner’s progress in re-integration and support their eventual return to society.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> I therefore conclude my submission by recommending that the Government includes the option for conditionally granting the vote to prisoners who are serving in an open prison in the draft bill.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">June 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> HC Debate 10 Feb 2011 c493</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Ibid, c494</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Ibid, c494</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">The History of the Parliamentary Franchise, Hansard Research Paper 13/14, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">1 March 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Case of Hirst v. The </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> (No. 2), European Court of Human Rights, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">6 October 2005</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">, para 82</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Ibid, para 60</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Case of Scoppola v. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Italy</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> (No. 3), European Court of Human Rights, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">22 May 2012</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Voting rights of convicted prisoners detained within the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">: second stage consultation. Consultation Paper CP6/09, Ministry of Justice, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">8 April 2009</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">, p15</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Political and Constitutional Reform Committee, para 22</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn10"></a><a href="#_ftnref10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">HC Debate 10 Feb 2011</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">, c512</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn11"></a><a href="#_ftnref11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Monitoring the Government’s response to court judgments finding breaches of human rights. Sixteenth report of</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">   </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> the House of Commons and House of Lords Joint Committee on Human Rights. HC 728, 2006-07</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn12"></a><a href="#_ftnref12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Case of Hirst v. The </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> (No. 2), European Court of Human Rights, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">6 October 2005</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">, para 82</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn13"></a><a href="#_ftnref13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Voting by Convicted Prisoners: Summary of Evidence – Political and Constitutional Reform Committee, 1 Feb</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">     2011, p7.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn14"></a><a href="#_ftnref14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Ibid, para 16</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn15"></a><a href="#_ftnref15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Dominic Raab, Daily Politics, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">22 Nov 2012</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn16"></a><a href="#_ftnref16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> HC Debate 10 Feb 2011 c512</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn17"></a><a href="#_ftnref17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-22844039</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn18"></a><a href="#_ftnref18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">http://www.insidetime.org/articleview.asp?a=1005</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn19"></a><a href="#_ftnref19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">http://www.insidetime.org </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">, Factsheet 12</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn20"></a><a href="#_ftnref20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">http://www.prisonreformtrust.org.uk/</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Factsheet: Release on Temporary License</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn21"></a><a href="#_ftnref21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">https://www.gov.uk/drink-drive-rehabilitation-scheme-guide-for-course-providers-and-courts</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn22"></a><a href="#_ftnref22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">http://m.guardian.co.uk/society/2011/jan/13/open-prison-no-holiday-camp</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn23"></a><a href="#_ftnref23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> HC Debate 10 Feb 2011 c572-3</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn24"></a><a href="#_ftnref24">[24]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Ibid, c531</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn25"></a><a href="#_ftnref25">[25]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Case of Scoppola v. Italy (No. 3), European Court of Human Rights, 22 May 2012</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">, Para 109</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn26"></a><a href="#_ftnref26">[26]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Ibid. para 109.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn27"></a><a href="#_ftnref27">[27]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Ibid. para 39.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn28"></a><a href="#_ftnref28">[28]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">http://www.citizenshipfoundation.org.uk/</span></p></body></html>